               <forename type="first">Catherine Maria</forename>
               <surname>Fanshawe</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1765"/>
            <death when="1834"/>
            <note> English poet, author and artist who copied poems into Davy's notebook under the pseudonym 'Fidelissima'.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_002">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Anna</forename>
               <surname>Beddoes</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1773"/>
            <death when="1824"/>
            <note>Anna Beddoes, née Edgeworth, the wife of Thomas Beddoes who befriended Davy when he arrived in Bristol. Critics have speculated that they had an affair because Davy wrote poems to Anna and she wrote poems for him that he copied out in his notebooks.  </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_005">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Claude Louis</forename>
               <surname>Berthollet</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1822"/>
            <note>French Chemist. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_003">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">William</forename>
               <surname>Allen</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1770"/>
            <death when="1843"/>
            <note>Allen was a Quaker who worked in the pharmaceutical industry. Davy asked him to give lectures on natural philosophy at the RI. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_015">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">William Haseldine</forename>
               <surname>Pepys</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1775"/>
            <death when="1856"/>
            <note>Pepys was a surgical and scientific instrument maker and chemist. Constructed large batteries used by Davy (amongst others). FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_049">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Louis Bernard </forename>
               <surname>Guyton de Morveau</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1737"/>
            <death when="1816"/>
            <note>French chemist and revolutionary politician who is credited with producing the first systematic method of chemical nomenclature. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_011">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Antoine-Francois de</forename>
               <surname>Fourcroy</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1755"/>
            <death when="1809"/>
            <note>French chemist who collaborated with Lavoisier in standardising chemical nomenclature. Davy as a teenager read some of his work.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_784">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Daniel Gabriel</forename>
               <surname>Fahrenheit</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1686"/>
            <death when="1736"/>
            <note>German physicist, inventor, and scientific instrument maker, who invented the mercury-in-glass thermometer. The temperature scale he proposed is named after him. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_206">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">William</forename>
               <surname>Henry</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1774"/>
            <death when="1836"/>
            <note>Manchester physician and chemist, whose Elements of Experimental Chemistry went through eleven editions. FRSL. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_008">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Charles</forename>
               <surname>Desormes</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1777"/>
            <death when="1838"/>
            <note>Desormes was a French physicist and chemist. He did most of his scientific work in collaboration with his son-in-law, Nicolas Clément.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_398">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Nicolas</forename>
               <surname>Clément</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1779"/>
            <death when="1841"/>
            <note>French chemist who worked with his father-in-law, Charles Desormes.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_012">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Joseph Louis</forename>
               <surname>Gay-Lussac</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1778"/>
            <death when="1850"/>
            <note>French chemist and physicist, known mostly for his discovery that water is made of two parts hydrogen and one part oxygen by volume (with Alexander von Humboldt), for two laws related to gases, and for his work on alcohol-water mixtures. Became involved in controversies with Davy over various chemical discoveries. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_066">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">John</forename>
               <surname>Dalton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1766"/>
            <death when="1844"/>
            <note>Mancunian chemist and natural philosopher who lectured at the Royal Institution. He formulated a version of the atomic theory of matter much disliked by Davy. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
      </listPerson>
